# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecommerce-magento
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] Content management systems (CMS) are used to organize and facilitate collaborative content creation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] Many of them are built on top of separate content management frameworks.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] The list is limited to notable services.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] that can be installed and managed on a web server.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] that includes software, hosting, and support with a single vendor.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] to be installed and managed on a user's own server.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] Systems listed on a light purple background are no longer in active development.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] A **content management framework** (**CMF**) is a system that facilitates the use of reusable components or customized software for managing Web content.
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] It shares aspects of a Web application framework and a content management system (CMS).
[src:ecommerce-magento/comparison-of-content-management-systems] Below is a list of notable systems that claim to be CMFs.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The term was coined and first employed by Robert Jacobson, Principal Consultant to the California State Assembly's Utilities & Commerce Committee, in the title and text of California's Electronic Commerce Act, carried by the late Committee Chairwoman Gwen Moore (D-L.A.) and enacted in 1984.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce typically uses the web for at least a part of a transaction's life cycle although it may also use other technologies such as e-mail.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Typical e-commerce transactions include the purchase of products (such as books from Amazon) or services (such as music downloads in the form of digital distribution such as the iTunes Store).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] There are three areas of e-commerce: online retailing, electronic markets, and online auctions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce is supported by electronic business.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The existence value of e-commerce is to allow consumers to shop online and pay online through the Internet, saving the time and space of customers and enterprises, greatly improving transaction efficiency, especially for busy office workers, and also saving a lot of valuable time.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Contemporary electronic commerce can be classified into two categories.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The first category is business based on types of goods sold (involves everything from ordering "digital" content for immediate online consumption, to ordering conventional goods and services, to "meta" services to facilitate other types of electronic commerce).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The second category is based on the nature of the participant (B2B, B2C, C2B and C2C).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] On the institutional level, big corporations and financial institutions use the internet to exchange financial data to facilitate domestic and international business.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Data integrity and security are pressing issues for electronic commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Aside from traditional e-commerce, the terms m-Commerce (mobile commerce) as well (around 2013) t-Commerce have also been used.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In the United States, California's Electronic Commerce Act (1984), enacted by the Legislature, the more recent California Privacy Rights Act (2020), enacted through a popular election proposition and to control specifically how electronic commerce may be conducted in California.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In the US in its entirety, electronic commerce activities are regulated more broadly by the Federal Trade Commission (FTC).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] These activities include the use of commercial e-mails, online advertising and consumer privacy.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The CAN-SPAM Act of 2003 establishes national standards for direct marketing over e-mail.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The Federal Trade Commission Act regulates all forms of advertising, including online advertising, and states that advertising must be truthful and non-deceptive.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Using its authority under Section 5 of the FTC Act, which prohibits unfair or deceptive practices, the FTC has brought a number of cases to enforce the promises in corporate privacy statements, including promises about the security of consumers' personal information.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] As a result, any corporate privacy policy related to e-commerce activity may be subject to enforcement by the FTC.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The Ryan Haight Online Pharmacy Consumer Protection Act of 2008, which came into law in 2008, amends the Controlled Substances Act to address online pharmacies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Conflict of laws in cyberspace is a major hurdle for harmonization of legal framework for e-commerce around the world.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In order to give a uniformity to e-commerce law around the world, many countries adopted the UNCITRAL Model Law on Electronic Commerce (1996).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] There is also **Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation**.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] APEC was established in 1989 with the vision of achieving stability, security and prosperity for the region through free and open trade and investment.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] APEC has an Electronic Commerce Steering Group as well as working on common privacy regulations throughout the APEC region.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In **Australia**, trade is covered under Australian Treasury Guidelines for electronic commerce and the Australian Competition & Consumer Commission regulates and offers advice on how to deal with businesses online, and offers specific advice on what happens if things go wrong.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In **the United Kingdom**, the Financial Services Authority (FSA) was formerly the regulating authority for most aspects of the EU's Payment Services Directive (PSD), until its replacement in 2013 by the Prudential Regulation Authority and the Financial Conduct Authority.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The UK implemented the PSD through the Payment Services Regulations 2009 (PSRs), which came into effect on 1 November 2009.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The PSR affects firms providing payment services and their customers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] These firms include banks, non-bank credit card issuers and non-bank merchant acquirers, e-money issuers, etc.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The PSRs created a new class of regulated firms known as payment institutions (PIs), who are subject to prudential requirements.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Article 87 of the PSD required the European Commission to report on the implementation and impact of the PSD by 1 November 2012.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In **India**, the Information Technology Act 2000 governs the basic applicability of e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] On the same day, the Administrative Measures on Internet Information Services were released, the first administrative regulations to address profit-generating activities conducted through the Internet, and lay the foundation for future regulations governing e-commerce in China.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] On 28 August 2004, the eleventh session of the tenth NPC Standing Committee adopted an Electronic Signature Law, which regulates data message, electronic signature authentication and legal liability issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It is considered the first law in China's e-commerce legislation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It was a milestone in the course of improving China's electronic commerce legislation, and also marks the entering of China's rapid development stage for electronic commerce legislation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce has become an important tool for small and large businesses worldwide, not only to sell to customers, but also to engage them.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Cross-border e-Commerce is also an essential field for e-Commerce businesses.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It has responded to the trend of globalization.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It shows that numerous firms have opened up new businesses, expanded new markets, and overcome trade barriers; more and more enterprises have started exploring the cross-border cooperation field.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In addition, compared with traditional cross-border trade, the information on cross-border e-commerce is more concealed.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In the era of globalization, cross-border e-commerce for inter-firm companies means the activities, interactions, or social relations of two or more e-commerce enterprises.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, the success of cross-border e-commerce promotes the development of small and medium-sized firms, and it has finally become a new transaction mode.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It has helped the companies solve financial problems and realize the reasonable allocation of resources field.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] SMEs (small and medium enterprises) can also precisely match the demand and supply in the market, having the industrial chain majorization and creating more revenues for companies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2012, e-commerce sales topped $1 trillion for the first time in history.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Mobile devices are playing an increasing role in the mix of e-commerce, this is also commonly called mobile commerce, or m-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2014, one estimate saw purchases made on mobile devices making up 25% of the market by 2017.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For traditional businesses, one research stated that information technology and cross-border e-commerce is a good opportunity for the rapid development and growth of enterprises.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Many companies have invested an enormous volume of investment in mobile applications.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The DeLone and McLean Model stated that three perspectives contribute to a successful e-business: information system quality, service quality and users' satisfaction.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Modern 3D graphics technologies, such as Facebook 3D Posts, are considered by some social media marketers and advertisers as a preferable way to promote consumer goods than static photos, and some brands like Sony are already paving the way for augmented reality commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Wayfair now lets you inspect a 3D version of its furniture in a home setting before buying.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Among emerging economies, China's e-commerce presence continued to expand every year.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] With 668 million Internet users as of 2014, China's online shopping sales reached $253 billion in the first half of 2015, accounting for 10% of total Chinese consumer retail sales in that period.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The Chinese retailers have been able to help consumers feel more comfortable shopping online. e-commerce transactions between China and other countries increased 32% to 2.3 trillion yuan ($375.8 billion) in 2012 and accounted for 9.6% of China's total international trade.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2013, Alibaba had an e-commerce market share of 80% in China.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2014, Alibaba still dominated the B2B marketplace in China with a market share of 44.82%, followed by several other companies including Made-in-China.com at 3.21%, and GlobalSources.com at 2.98%, with the total transaction value of China's B2B market exceeding 4.5 billion yuan.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2012, Alibaba Group delisted Alibaba.com from the Hong Kong stock exchange after acquiring full control.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2014, it was privately held again following a $2.5 billion buyback.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The company's NYSE debut under the stock ticker BABA made headlines for being, at that time, the biggest IPO in U.S. history.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Alibaba's International Digital Commerce Group (AIDC), which includes Alibaba.com's B2B operations, reported 22% year-over-year revenue growth in the quarter ending March 31, 2025 (Q4 FY2025).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] China was also the largest e-commerce market in the world by value of sales, with an estimated US$899 billion in 2016.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It accounted for 42.4% of worldwide retail e-commerce in that year, the most of any country.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Research shows that Chinese consumer motivations are different enough from Western audiences to require unique e-commerce app designs instead of simply porting Western apps into the Chinese market.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The expansion of e-commerce in China has resulted in the development of Taobao villages, clusters of e-commerce businesses operating in rural areas.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Because Taobao villages have increased the incomes or rural people and entrepreneurship in rural China, Taobao villages have become a component of rural revitalization strategies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2015, the State Council promoted the Internet Plus initiative, a five-year plan to integrate traditional manufacturing and service industries with big data, cloud computing, and Internet of things technology.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The State Council provided support for Internet Plus through policy support in area including cross-border e-commerce and rural e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2019, the city of Hangzhou established a pilot program artificial intelligence-based Internet Court to adjudicate disputes related to e-commerce and internet-related intellectual property claims.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2010, the United Kingdom had the highest per capita e-commerce spending in the world.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] As of 2013, the Czech Republic was the European country where e-commerce delivers the biggest contribution to the enterprises' total revenue.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Almost a quarter (24%) of the country's total turnover is generated via the online channel.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The rate of growth of the number of internet users in the Arab countries has been rapid – 13.1% in 2015.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] A significant portion of the e-commerce market in the Middle East comprises people in the 30–34 year age group.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Egypt has the largest number of internet users in the region, followed by Saudi Arabia and Morocco; these constitute 3/4th of the region's share.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Yet, internet penetration is low: 35% in Egypt and 65% in Saudi Arabia.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The Gulf Cooperation Council countries have a rapidly growing market and are characterized by a population that becomes wealthier (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] As such, retailers have launched Arabic-language websites as a means to target this population.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Secondly, there are predictions of increased mobile purchases and an expanding internet audience (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The growth and development of the two aspects make the GCC countries become larger players in the electronic commerce market with time progress.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Specifically, research shows that the e-commerce market was expected to grow to over $20 billion by 2020 among these GCC countries (Yuldashev).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The e-commerce market has also gained much popularity among western countries, and in particular Europe and the U.S.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] These countries have been highly characterized by consumer-packaged goods (CPG) (Geisler, 34).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, trends show that there are future signs of a reverse.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Similar to the GCC countries, there has been increased purchase of goods and services in online channels rather than offline channels.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Activist investors are trying hard to consolidate and slash their overall cost and the governments in western countries continue to impose more regulation on CPG manufacturers (Geisler, 36).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In these senses, CPG investors are being forced to adapt to e-commerce as it is effective as well as a means for them to thrive.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The future trends in the GCC countries will be similar to that of the western countries.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Despite the forces that push business to adapt e-commerce as a means to sell goods and products, the manner in which customers make purchases is similar in countries from these two regions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For instance, there has been an increased usage of smartphones which comes in conjunction with an increase in the overall internet audience from the regions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Yuldashev writes that consumers are scaling up to more modern technology that allows for mobile marketing.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, the percentage of smartphone and internet users who make online purchases is expected to vary in the first few years.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It will be independent on the willingness of the people to adopt this new trend (The Statistics Portal).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For example, UAE has the greatest smartphone penetration of 73.8 per cent and has 91.9 per cent of its population has access to the internet.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] On the other hand, smartphone penetration in Europe has been reported to be at 64.7 per cent (The Statistics Portal).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Regardless, the disparity in percentage between these regions is expected to level out in future because e-commerce technology is expected to grow to allow for more users.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The e-commerce business within these two regions will result in competition.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Government bodies at the country level will enhance their measures and strategies to ensure sustainability and consumer protection (Krings, et al.).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] These increased measures will raise the environmental and social standards in the countries, factors that will determine the success of the e-commerce market in these countries.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For example, an adoption of tough sanctions will make it difficult for companies to enter the e-commerce market while lenient sanctions will allow ease of companies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] As such, the future trends between GCC countries and the Western countries will be independent of these sanctions (Krings, et al.).
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] These countries need to make rational conclusions in coming up with effective sanctions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] India had an Internet user base of about 460 million as of December 2017.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Despite being the third largest user base in the world, the penetration of the Internet is low compared to markets like the United States, United Kingdom or France but is growing at a much faster rate, adding around six million new entrants every month.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In India, cash on delivery is the most preferred payment method, accumulating 75% of the e-retail activities.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The India retail market was expected to rise from 2.5% in 2016 to 5% in 2020.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2013, Brazil's e-commerce was growing quickly with retail e-commerce sales expected to grow at a double-digit pace through 2014.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] By 2016, eMarketer expected retail e-commerce sales in Brazil to reach $17.3 billion.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Logistics in e-commerce mainly concerns fulfillment.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Online markets and retailers have to find the best possible way to fill orders and deliver products.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Small companies usually control their own logistic operation because they do not have the ability to hire an outside company.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Most large companies hire a fulfillment service that takes care of a company's logistic needs.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The optimization of logistics processes that contains long-term investment in an efficient storage infrastructure system and adoption of inventory management strategies is crucial to prioritize customer satisfaction throughout the entire process, from order placement to final delivery.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce markets grew at noticeable rates.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The online market was expected to grow by 56% in 2015–2020.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2017, retail e-commerce sales worldwide amounted to 2.3 trillion US dollars and e-retail revenues were projected to grow to 4.891 trillion US dollars in 2021.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Traditional markets were only expected 2% growth during the same time.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Brick and mortar retailers are struggling because of online retailer's ability to offer lower prices and higher efficiency.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Many larger retailers are able to maintain a presence offline and online by linking physical and online offerings.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce allows customers to overcome geographical barriers and to purchase products anytime and from anywhere.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Online and traditional markets have different strategies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Traditional retailers offer fewer assortment of products because of shelf space where.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Online retailers often hold no inventory but send customer orders directly to the manufacturer.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Dropshipping is a means of shipping goods from a manufacturer or wholesaler directly to a customer instead of to a retailer.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] This process results in the vendor not holding any stock but serving as an intermediary between the buyer and the third-party supplier.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The dropshipping market is expected to reach $1.51 Tn by 2032, according to a Global Market Insights report, which studied the main dropshipping markets, including Alibaba.com, Chinabrands.com, Doba, Printful, Salehoo, Shopify, and Spocket.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The pricing strategies are also different for traditional and online retailers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Traditional retailers base their prices on store traffic and the cost to keep inventory.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Online retailers base prices on the speed of delivery.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce merchants may operate fully online, or online along with a brick and mortar store.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Online marketers can offer lower prices, greater product selection, and high efficiency rates.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Many customers prefer online markets if the products can be delivered quickly at relatively low price.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, online retailers cannot offer the physical experience that traditional retailers can.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It can be difficult to judge the quality of a product without the physical experience, which may cause customers to experience product or seller uncertainty.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Another issue regarding the online market is concerns about the security of online transactions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Many customers remain loyal to well-known retailers because of this issue.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Security is a primary problem for e-commerce in developed and developing countries.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce security is protecting businesses' websites and customers from unauthorized access, use, alteration, or destruction.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Threats include: malicious codes, unwanted programs (ad ware, spyware), phishing, hacking, and cyber vandalism.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Tools to avert these threats include firewalls, encryption software, digital certificates, and passwords.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For a long time, companies had been troubled by the gap between the benefits which supply chain technology has and the solutions to deliver those benefits.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, the emergence of e-commerce has provided a more practical and effective way of delivering the benefits of the new supply chain technologies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce has the capability to integrate all inter-company and intra-company functions, meaning that the three flows (physical flow, financial flow and information flow) of the supply chain could be also affected by e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The affections on physical flows improved the way of product and inventory movement level for companies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] For the information flows, e-commerce optimized the capacity of information processing than companies used to have, and for the financial flows, e-commerce allows companies to have more efficient payment and settlement solutions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Yet these new capabilities are still not fully exploited.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Thirdly, technology companies would keep investing on new e-commerce software solutions as they are expecting investment return.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Fourthly, e-commerce would help to solve many aspects of issues that companies may feel difficult to cope with, such as political barriers or cross-country changes.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Finally, e-commerce provides companies a more efficient and effective way to collaborate with each other within the supply chain.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce helps create new job opportunities due to information related services, software app and digital products.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The areas with the greatest predicted job-loss are retail, postal, and travel agencies.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The development of e-commerce will create jobs that require highly skilled workers to manage large amounts of information, customer demands, and production processes.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In contrast, people with poor technical skills cannot enjoy the wages welfare.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] On the other hand, because e-commerce requires sufficient stocks that could be delivered to customers in time, the warehouse becomes an important element.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Warehouse needs more staff to manage, supervise and organize, thus the condition of warehouse environment will be concerned by employees.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce brings convenience for customers as they do not have to leave home and only need to browse websites online, especially for buying products which are not sold in nearby shops.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] It could help customers buy a wider range of products and save customers' time.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Consumers also gain power through online shopping.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] They are able to research products and compare prices among retailers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Thanks to the practice of user-generated ratings and reviews from companies like Bazaarvoice, Trustpilot, and Yelp, customers can also see what other people think of a product, and decide before buying if they want to spend money on it.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Also, online shopping often provides sales promotion or discounts code, thus it is more price effective for customers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Moreover, e-commerce provides products' detailed information; even the in-store staff cannot offer such detailed explanation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Customers can also review and track the order history online.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] E-commerce technologies cut transaction costs by allowing both manufactures and consumers to skip through the intermediaries.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] This is achieved through by extending the search area best price deals and by group purchase.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The success of e-commerce in urban and regional levels depend on how the local firms and consumers have adopted to e-commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] However, e-commerce lacks human interaction for customers, especially who prefer face-to-face connection.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Customers are also concerned with the security of online transactions and tend to remain loyal to well-known retailers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In recent years, clothing retailers such as Tommy Hilfiger have started adding Virtual Fit platforms to their e-commerce sites to reduce the risk of customers buying the wrong sized clothes, although these vary greatly in their fit for purpose.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] When the customer regret the purchase of a product, it involves returning goods and refunding process.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] This process is inconvenient as customers need to pack and post the goods.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] If the products are expensive, large or fragile, it refers to safety issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In 2018, E-commerce generated 1.3 million short tons (1.2 megatonnes) of container cardboard in North America, an increase from 1.1 million (1.00)) in 2017.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Only 35 percent of North American cardboard manufacturing capacity was from recycled content.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The recycling rate in Europe was 80 percent and Asia was 93 percent.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Amazon, the largest user of boxes, had a strategy to cut back on packing material and reduced packaging material used by 19 percent by weight since 2016.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Amazon is requiring retailers to manufacture their product packaging in a way that does not require additional shipping packaging.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Amazon also has an 85-person team researching ways to reduce and improve their packaging and shipping materials.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Accelerated movement of packages around the world includes accelerated movement of living things, such as invasive species.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Weeds, pests, and diseases all sometimes travel in packages of seeds.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Some of these packages are part of brushing manipulation of e-commerce reviews.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Many companies have turned to sales promotions and increased digital efforts to lure shoppers while shutting down brick-and-mortar locations.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] The trend has forced some traditional retailers to shutter its brick and mortar operations.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] In March 2020, global retail website traffic hit 14.3 billion visits signifying an unprecedented growth of e-commerce during the lockdown of 2020.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Later studies show that online sales increased by 25% and online grocery shopping increased by over 100% during the crisis in the United States.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Meanwhile, as many as 29% of surveyed shoppers state that they will never go back to shopping in person again; in the UK, 43% of consumers state that they expect to keep on shopping the same way even after the lockdown is over.
[src:ecommerce-magento/e-commerce] Retail sales of e-commerce shows that COVID-19 has a significant impact on e-commerce and its sales were expected to reach $6.5 trillion by 2023.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] More than 150,000 online stores have been created on the platform.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The platform code has been downloaded more than 2.5 million times, and $155 billion worth of goods were sold through Magento-based systems in 2019.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] As of April 2021, Magento holds a 2.32% market share in global e-commerce platforms.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Roy Rubin, the former CEO of Varien, sold a share of the company to eBay, which eventually completely acquired and then sold the company to Permira in 2015; Permira later sold it to Adobe.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento began development in early 2007.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It was originally developed by **Varien Inc.**, a U.S.-based private company headquartered in Culver City, California, with 99% of contributions and developers from Ukraine.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The first public beta version was released on August 31, 2007.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Varien had previously worked with osCommerce and initially considered forking it, but ultimately chose to create Magento from scratch.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The first general-availability release of Magento was published on March 31, 2008.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In its early years, Magento won several awards, including the *Best of Open Source Software Awards* and the *SourceForge Community Choice Awards*.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In February 2011, eBay announced that it had acquired a 49% stake in Magento in 2010.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] On June 6, 2011, eBay revealed it would acquire the remaining shares and integrate Magento into its X.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento co-founder Roy Rubin stated the platform would continue operating from Los Angeles under his and Yoav Kutner's leadership.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Yoav Kutner left Magento in April 2012, stating that changes in leadership had shifted the company's original vision post-acquisition.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Following the eBay–PayPal split driven by activist investor Carl Icahn, Magento was spun off and sold to Permira, a private equity firm, on November 3, 2015.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In May 2018, Adobe Inc. announced it would acquire Magento for $1.68 billion to integrate the platform into Adobe Experience Cloud.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The acquisition was finalized on June 19, 2018.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento employs the MySQL or MariaDB relational database management system, the PHP programming language, and elements of the Zend Framework.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It uses multiple other PHP frameworks such as Laminas (formerly known as Zend Framework) and Symfony.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It applies the conventions of object-oriented programming and model–view–controller (MVC) architecture.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento also uses the entity–attribute–value model to store data and as of version 2.4 it requires Elasticsearch for its catalog search capability.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] On top of that, Magento 2 introduced the model–view–viewmodel (MVVM) pattern to its front-end code using the JavaScript library Knockout.js.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Open Source, previously Magento Community Edition, is an open-source e-commerce platform.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Developers can implement the core files and extend their functionality by adding new plug-in modules provided by other developers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] As of 2017, both the latest release and each of the historical releases of the version 1.x and 2.x branches of Magento Open Source were available on the Magento Commerce, Inc. website for download.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Development of the version 2 branch of Magento Open Source is coordinated publicly on GitHub.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Adobe announced after its acquisition that Magento would remain open source.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento 1.9.4, the last version of the Magento 1.x branch, reached end-of-life on June 30, 2020.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento 2 was announced in 2010 with an initial release planned for 2011.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] However, delays postponed its rollout, and a merchant beta version was eventually made available in July 2015.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The stable release of Magento 2 occurred on November 17, 2015.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It introduced a re-architected codebase with improved performance, scalability, and modernized development tools.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] For a period, Magento 1 and Magento 2 were maintained concurrently to support merchant migration.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] OpenMage is a fork of Magento 1.x (version 1.9.4.5) maintained by the community on GitHub to offer long-term support and continued bug fixes for Magento 1.x installations.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Adobe Commerce is an e-commerce platform as a service released on April 11, 2016.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It initially launched as Magento Commerce.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In April 2021, Magento Commerce was rebranded to Adobe Commerce, as part of a long-term project to integrate Magento within the Adobe Experience Cloud business unit.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Adobe Commerce is available in an on-premises version and as a service hosted by Adobe in the cloud.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The hosted version launched as Magento Enterprise Cloud Edition and later became Adobe Commerce Managed Services.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] There were also two former platforms, Magento Professional Edition, and Magento Go.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Solution Partners are certified agencies that specialize in delivering eCommerce solutions on the Magento platform (now Adobe Commerce).
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] These partners have demonstrated expertise in implementing, customizing, and maintaining Magento-based websites for merchants across B2B, B2C, and D2C channels.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Many Solution Partners also develop proprietary extensions, integrations, and performance enhancements that extend the capabilities of the core platform.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Adobe maintains a directory of certified partners to help merchants identify implementation experts with proven success in Magento Commerce projects.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Technology Partners—now Adobe Commerce Technology Partners—are third-party companies that provide integrated products and services to extend the capabilities of Adobe Commerce stores.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] These partners support key areas such as marketing automation, payments, content management, shipping, taxation, hosting, performance optimization, and more.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In 2015, it was reported that outdated or unpatched Magento web stores were susceptible to a cross-site scripting attack, which allowed attackers to perform online skimming to steal user credit card information.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] According to a security expert, more than 4000 Magento web stores were vulnerable to such an attack in October 2016.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It's suspected that up to 260,000 Magento web stores could be vulnerable to such an attack in April 2017.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In 2019, Magento reported a potential vulnerability in its administration URL location for its 2.1.x, 2.2.x, and 2.3.x versions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It also reported a critical security breach for customers running version 1.0.2 (and earlier versions) of the Magestore Store Locator extension.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Similar incidences of a Magecart attack and Magento killer have also been faced by e-commerce store owners.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In the following years, Adobe has continued to release regular security updates for Adobe Commerce and Magento Open Source to address critical vulnerabilities.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] These updates have included fixes for privilege escalation, arbitrary file system access, cross-site scripting (XSS), and other high-severity issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Notable examples include security bulletins APSB25-71 (August 2025), APSB25-50 (April 2025), and earlier releases, which addressed multiple vulnerabilities that could potentially allow attackers to bypass security features, read sensitive files, or disrupt store functionality if left unpatched.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] "Imagine eCommerce" is the annual Magento eCommerce conference that has run since 2011.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The first event was held in February 2011 in Los Angeles with more than 600 Magento merchants, partners, and developers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The goals of the event are sharing e-commerce ideas and providing networking opportunity sessions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Besides Imagine, Magento also organizes local "Magento Live" events in which the participants will have opportunities to learn more about e-commerce in general, get introduced to local Magento partners, and learn about upcoming changes to the Magento software itself.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Live events have been held in Australia (Sydney), UK (London), The Netherlands (Amsterdam), Spain (Barcelona), France (Paris) and Germany (München).
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] There is a non-profit organization that was established in 2019 and that contributes up to more than 24 global "Meet Magento" events per year named "Magento Association" The association is open to all companies who are active in e-commerce in any way and want using Magento commerce now or in future.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The project has been run on all developed markets of Magento like Germany, Austria, Switzerland, France, Sweden, Denmark, Italy, Spain, the Netherlands, Poland, Ukraine, Romania, India and also Vietnam.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] There are four different Magento certifications: three of them aim to prove developers' competency in implementing modules; one (Certified Solution Specialist) targets business users (consultants, analysts, project managers).
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Front End Developer Certification is mainly focused on improving the user interface (UI) of back-end developers who implement the core modules.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The Plus certification tests a deep understanding of Magento Enterprise modules and the entire architecture.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The docker-magento project allows Magento development environments to be easily set up.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] It works for both new and existing Magento instances, and has been maintained and supported by M.academy since September 20, 2015.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento Open Source 2.0.0 was released on November 17, 2015, and the latest version 2.4.8-p4 was released on March 10, 2026.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Magento 1 migration to Magento 2 can be done by the official Data Migration Tool.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] The migration can be performed by developers with extensive Magento 1 and 2 experience.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] Official Adobe Commerce release notes are available.
[src:ecommerce-magento/magento] In 2011, a *TechCrunch* article reported that according to its sources, former Magento employees claim they have been collectively "cheated out" of nearly 7–10% of Magento, a stake that would have been worth approximately $18 million when eBay acquired the company earlier that year.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP code is usually processed on a web server by a PHP interpreter implemented as a module, a daemon or a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) executable.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] On a web server, the result of the interpreted and executed PHP code—which may be any type of data, such as generated HTML or binary image data—can form the whole or part of an HTTP response.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Various web template systems, web content management systems, and web frameworks exist that can be employed to orchestrate or facilitate the generation of that response.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP can be used for programming tasks outside the web context, though non-web uses are rare.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP code can also be directly executed from the command line.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The standard PHP interpreter, powered by the Zend Engine, is free software released under the PHP License.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP has been widely ported and can be deployed on most web servers on a variety of operating systems and platforms.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The PHP language at first evolved without a written formal specification or standard, with the original implementation acting as the *de facto* standard that other implementations aimed to follow.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP development began in 1993 when Rasmus Lerdorf wrote several Common Gateway Interface (CGI) programs in C, which he used to maintain his personal homepage.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] He extended them to work with HTML forms and to communicate with databases, and called this implementation "Personal Home Page/Forms Interpreter" or PHP/FI.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP/FI could be used to build simple, dynamic web applications.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] To accelerate bug reporting and improve the code, Lerdorf initially announced the release of PHP/FI as "Personal Home Page Tools (PHP Tools) version 1.0" on the Usenet discussion group *comp.infosystems.www.authoring.cgi* on 8 June 1995.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This release included basic functionality such as Perl-like variables, form handling, and the ability to embed HTML.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] By this point, the syntax had changed to resemble that of Perl, but was simpler, more limited, and less consistent.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The fact that PHP was not originally designed, but instead was developed organically has led to inconsistent naming of functions and inconsistent ordering of their parameters.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In some cases, the function names were chosen to match the lower-level libraries which PHP was "wrapping", while in some very early versions of PHP the length of the function names was used internally as a hash function, so names were chosen to improve the distribution of hash values.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Zeev Suraski and Andi Gutmans rewrote the parser in 1997 and formed the base of PHP 3, changing the language's name to the recursive acronym *PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor*.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Afterwards, public testing of PHP 3 began, and the official launch came in June 1998.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Suraski and Gutmans then started a new rewrite of PHP's core, producing the Zend Engine in 1999.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] They also founded Zend Technologies in Ramat Gan, Israel.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] On 22 May 2000, PHP 4.0, powered by the Zend Engine 1.0, was released.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] By August 2008, this branch had reached version 4.4.9.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 4 is now no longer under development nor are any security updates planned to be released.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] On 1 July 2004, PHP 5.0 was released, powered by the new Zend Engine 2.0.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 5.0 included significant changes to the language, most notably an overhauled approach to object-oriented programming, as well as iterators and exceptions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 5.1 and PHP 5.2 were released the following years, adding smaller improvements and new features, such as the PHP Data Objects (PDO) extension (which defines a lightweight and consistent interface for accessing databases) In 2008, PHP 5.x became the only stable version under development.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Many high-profile open-source projects ceased to support PHP 4 in new code from February 5, 2008, because of the GoPHP5 initiative, provided by a consortium of PHP developers promoting the transition from PHP 4 to PHP 5.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP's native string functions worked only on raw bytes, making use with multibyte character encodings difficult.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In 2005, a project headed by Andrei Zmievski was initiated to bring native Unicode support throughout PHP, by embedding the International Components for Unicode (ICU) library, and representing text strings as UTF-16 internally.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Since this would cause major changes both to the internals of the language and to user code, it was planned to release this as version 6.0 of the language, along with other major features then in development.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] However, a shortage of developers who understood the necessary changes, and performance problems arising from conversion to and from UTF-16, which is rarely used in a web context, led to delays in the project.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] As a result, a PHP 5.3 release was created in 2009, and in March 2010, the project in its current form was officially abandoned, and a PHP 5.4 release was prepared to contain most remaining non-Unicode features from PHP 6.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Initial hopes were that a new plan would be formed for Unicode integration, but by 2014 none had been adopted.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Because it contained features originally intended to be part of 6.0, PHP 5.3 was a significant release, adding support for namespaces, closures, late static binding, and many fixes and improvements to standard functions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] With the Unicode branch officially abandoned, a new release process was adopted in 2011, planning a yearly release cycle, and a clear distinction between "feature releases" (x.y.z to x.y+1.z) and "major releases" (x.y.z to x+1.0.0).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Remaining features which had been planned for the 6.0 release were included in PHP 5.4, released in March 2012, such as trait support and a new "short array syntax".
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This was followed by more incremental changes in PHP 5.5 (June 2013) and 5.6 (August 2014).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] For PHP versions 5.3 and 5.4, the only available Microsoft Windows binary distributions were 32-bit IA-32 builds, requiring Windows 32-bit compatibility mode while using Internet Information Services (IIS) on a 64-bit Windows platform.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP version 5.5 made the 64-bit x86-64 builds available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Official security support for PHP 5.6 ended on 31 December 2018.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] During 2014 and 2015, a new major PHP version was developed, PHP 7.0.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The numbering of this version involved some debate among internal developers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] While the PHP 6 Unicode experiments had never been released, several articles and book titles referenced the PHP 6 names, which might have caused confusion if a new release were to reuse the name.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] After a vote, the name PHP 7 was chosen.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The foundation of PHP 7.0 was a PHP branch that was originally dubbed *PHP next generation* (*phpng*).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] It was written by Dmitry Stogov, Xinchen Hui and Nikita Popov, and aimed to optimize PHP performance by refactoring the Zend Engine while retaining near-complete language compatibility.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] By 14 July 2014, WordPress-based benchmarks, which served as the main benchmark suite for the phpng project, showed an almost 100% increase in performance.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Changes from phpng make it easier to improve performance in future versions, as more compact data structures and other changes are seen as better suited for a successful migration to a just-in-time (JIT) compiler.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Because of the significant changes, the reworked Zend Engine was called *Zend Engine 3*, succeeding Zend Engine 2 used in PHP 5.x.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also included changes which were not backward compatible, as allowed for "major versions" under the versioning scheme agreed in 2011.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Changes to the core language included a more consistent handling of variable dereferencing, a more predictable behavior of the `foreach` statement, and platform consistency of bitwise shifts and floating-point to integer conversion.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Several unmaintained or deprecated server application programming interfaces (SAPIs) and extensions were removed from the PHP core, most notably the legacy `mysql` extension.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Other legacy features were also removed, such as ASP-style delimiters `<%` and `%>` and `<script language="php"> ... </script>`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 7.0 marked the beginning of an expansion in PHP's type system.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 8.0 was released on 26 November 2020, as a major version with breaking changes from previous versions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] One of the most high-profile changes was the addition of a JIT compiler, which can provide substantial performance improvements for some use cases.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Substantial improvements were expected more for mathematical-type operations than for common web-development use cases.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Additionally, the performance advantage of the JIT compiler provides the potential to move some code from C to PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] A significant addition to the language in 8.0 is attributes, which allow metadata to be added to program elements such as classes, methods, and parameters.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Later versions added built-in attributes which change the behaviour of the language, such as the `#[\SensitiveParameter]` attribute in PHP 8.2, `#[\Override]` in PHP 8.3, `#[\Deprecated]` in PHP 8.4, and the `#[\NoDiscard]` and `#[\DelayedTargetValidation]` attributes in PHP 8.5.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] A significant extension to the language's type system is the addition of composite types: union types in PHP 8.0 (e.g.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `int|string` meaning "either integer or string"), intersection types in PHP 8.1 (e.g.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `Traversable&Countable` meaning the value must implement both the `Traversable` and `Countable` interfaces), and disjunctive normal form (DNF) types in PHP 8.2 (unions of intersections, such as `array|(Traversable&Countable)`).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Additional special type keywords have been added, such as `mixed` and `static` in PHP 8.0, `never` (a bottom type indicating that a function never returns) in PHP 8.1, and `null`, `false`, and `true` as stand-alone types in PHP 8.2.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The addition of a rich type system is part of a general trend towards a stricter language, and PHP 8.0 included breaking changes to the handling of string to number comparisons, numeric strings, and incompatible method signatures.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Later versions have introduced deprecation notices for behaviour which is planned as a breaking change in a future major version, such as passing `null` to non-nullable internal function parameters and referring to properties which have not been declared on the class.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Beginning on 28 June 2011, the PHP Development Team implemented a timeline for the release of new versions of PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Under this system, at least one release should occur every month.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Once per year, a minor release should occur which may include new features.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Every minor release should at least be supported for two years with security and bug fixes, followed by at least one year of only security fixes, for a total of a three-year release process for every minor release.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] No new features, unless small and self-contained, are to be introduced into a minor release during the three-year release process.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] A 2024 RFC extended the length of the security fix only period to two years, fixed all end of life dates to 31 December, and removed the exception that allowed for "small and self-contained" features to be introduced in patch versions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] W3Techs reports that as of November 2025 (about three years since PHP 7 was discontinued and 23 months after the PHP 8.3 release), unsupported versions such as PHP 7 are still used by well over half of PHP websites, which are outdated and known to be insecure.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Those included the 9.7% of PHP websites using the even more outdated (discontinued for 7 years) and insecure PHP 5, released over two decades ago.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The mascot of the PHP project is the *elePHPant*, a blue elephant with the PHP logo on its side, designed by Vincent Pontier in 1998.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The elePHPant is sometimes differently coloured when in plush toy form.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Many variations of this physical mascot have been made over the years.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Only the elePHPants based on the original design by Vincent Pontier are considered official by the community.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] These are collectable and some of them are extremely rare.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The PHP interpreter only executes PHP code within its delimiters.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Anything outside its delimiters is not processed by PHP, although the non-PHP text can still be subject to control structures described in PHP code.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `<?php` is used to open and `?>` to close PHP sections.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] A shorthand `<?=` exists, which is a shorthand for `<?php echo`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The shortened form `<?` also exists, which makes script files less portable since support can be disabled in the local PHP configuration.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The shortened form is discouraged by the PHP Group for this reason.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Conversely, there is no recommendation against the echo short tag `<?=`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Prior to PHP 5.4.0, the short syntax for `echo` only works with the `short_open_tag` configuration setting enabled, while for PHP 5.4.0 and later it is always available.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The purpose of delimiters is to separate PHP code from non-PHP content, such as JavaScript code or HTML markup.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The first form of delimiters, `<?php` and `?>`, in XHTML and other XML documents, creates correctly formed XML processing instructions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This means that the resulting mixture of PHP code and other markup in the server-side file is itself well-formed XML.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Variables are prefixed with a dollar symbol, and a type does not need to be specified in advance.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced type declarations that allow functions to force their parameters to be objects of a specific class, arrays, interfaces or callback functions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] However, before PHP 7, type declarations could not be used with scalar types such as integers or strings.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Below is an example of how PHP variables are declared and initialized.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Unlike function and class names, variable names are case-sensitive.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Both double-quoted ("") and heredoc strings provide the ability to interpolate a variable's value into the string.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP treats newlines as whitespace in the manner of a free-form language, and statements are terminated by a semicolon.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP has three types of comments: `/* */` marks block and inline comments; `//` or `#` are used for one-line comments.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The `echo` statement is one of several keywords PHP provides to output text.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In terms of keywords and language syntax, PHP is similar to C-style syntax.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `if` conditions, `for` and `while` loops and function returns are similar in syntax to languages such as C, C++, C#, Java and Perl.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] It stores integers in a platform-dependent range, either as a 32, 64 or 128-bit signed integer equivalent to the C-language long type.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Unsigned integers are converted to signed values in certain situations, which is different behaviour to many other programming languages.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Integer variables can be assigned using decimal (positive and negative), octal, hexadecimal, and binary notations.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Floating-point numbers are also stored in a platform-specific range.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] They can be specified using floating-point notation, or two forms of scientific notation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP has a native Boolean type that is similar to the native Boolean types in Java and C++.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Using the Boolean type conversion rules, non-zero values are interpreted as true and zero as false, as in Perl and C++.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The null data type represents a variable that has no value; `NULL` is the only allowed value for this data type.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Variables of the "resource" type represent references to resources from external sources.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] These are typically created by functions from a particular extension, and can only be processed by functions from the same extension; examples include file, image, and database resources.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Arrays can contain elements of any type that PHP can handle, including resources, objects, and even other arrays.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Order is preserved in lists of values and in hashes with both keys and values, and the two can be intermingled.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP also supports strings, which can be used with single quotes, double quotes, nowdoc or heredoc syntax.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The **Standard PHP Library** (SPL) attempts to solve standard problems and implements efficient data access interfaces and classes.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP defines a large array of functions in the core language and many are also available in various extensions; these functions are well documented online PHP documentation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] However, the built-in library has a wide variety of naming conventions and associated inconsistencies, as described under history above.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In lieu of function pointers, functions in PHP can be referenced by a string containing their name.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In this manner, normal PHP functions can be used, for example, as callbacks or within function tables.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] User-defined functions may be created at any time without being prototyped.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Functions may be defined inside code blocks, permitting a run-time decision as to whether or not a function should be defined.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There is a `function_exists` function that determines whether a function with a given name has already been defined.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Function calls must use parentheses, with the exception of zero-argument class constructor functions called with the PHP operator `new`, in which case parentheses are optional.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In the example above, `getAdder()` function creates a closure using passed argument `$x`, which takes an additional argument `$y`, and returns the created closure to the caller.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Such a function is a first-class object, meaning that it can be stored in a variable, passed as a parameter to other functions, etc.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Unusually for a dynamically typed language, PHP supports type declarations on function parameters, which are enforced at runtime.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This has been supported for classes and interfaces since PHP 5.0, for arrays since PHP 5.1, for "callables" since PHP 5.4, and scalar (integer, float, string and boolean) types since PHP 7.0.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 7.0 also has type declarations for function return types, expressed by placing the type name after the list of parameters, preceded by a colon.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] By default, scalar type declarations follow weak typing principles.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] So, for example, if a parameter's type is `int`, PHP would allow not only integers, but also convertible numeric strings, floats or Booleans to be passed to that function, and would convert them.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] However, PHP 7 has a "strict typing" mode which, when used, disallows such conversions for function calls and returns within a file.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Basic object-oriented programming functionality was added in PHP 3 and improved in PHP 4.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This allowed for PHP to gain further abstraction, making creative tasks easier for programmers using the language.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Object handling was completely rewritten for PHP 5, expanding the feature set and enhancing performance.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In previous versions of PHP, objects were handled like value types.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The drawback of this method was that code had to make heavy use of PHP's "reference" variables if it wanted to modify an object it was passed rather than creating a copy of it.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] In the new approach, objects are referenced by handle, and not by value.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP 5 introduced private and protected member variables and methods, along with abstract classes, final classes, abstract methods, and final methods.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] It also introduced a standard way of declaring constructors and destructors, similar to that of other object-oriented languages such as C++, and a standard exception handling model.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Furthermore, PHP 5 added interfaces and allowed for multiple interfaces to be implemented.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There are special interfaces that allow objects to interact with the runtime system.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Objects implementing ArrayAccess can be used with array syntax and objects implementing Iterator or IteratorAggregate can be used with the `foreach` language construct.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There is no virtual table feature in the engine, so static variables are bound with a name instead of a reference at compile time.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] If the developer creates a copy of an object using the reserved word `clone`, the Zend engine will check whether a `__clone()` method has been defined.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] If not, it will call a default `__clone()` which will copy the object's properties.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] If a `__clone()` method is defined, then it will be responsible for setting the necessary properties in the created object.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] For convenience, the engine will supply a function that imports the properties of the source object, so the programmer can start with a by-value replica of the source object and only override properties that need to be changed.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The visibility of PHP properties and methods is defined using the keywords `public`, `private`, and `protected`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The default is public, if only var is used; `var` is a synonym for `public`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Items declared `public` can be accessed everywhere.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `protected` limits access to inherited classes (and to the class that defines the item).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] `private` limits visibility only to the class that defines the item.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Objects of the same type have access to each other's private and protected members even though they are not the same instance.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The only complete PHP implementation is the original, known simply as PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] It is the most widely used and is powered by the Zend Engine.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] To disambiguate it from other implementations, it is sometimes unofficially called "Zend PHP".
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The Zend Engine compiles PHP source code on-the-fly into an internal format that it can execute, thus it works as an interpreter.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] It is also the "reference implementation" of PHP, as PHP has no formal specification, and so the semantics of Zend PHP define the semantics of PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Due to the complex and nuanced semantics of PHP, defined by how Zend works, it is difficult for competing implementations to offer complete compatibility.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP's single-request-per-script-execution model, and the fact that the Zend Engine is an interpreter, leads to inefficiency; as a result, various products have been developed to help improve PHP performance.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] An opcode cache, Zend Opcache, is built into PHP since version 5.5.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Another example of a widely used opcode cache is the Alternative PHP Cache (APC), which is available as a PECL extension.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] While Zend PHP is still the most popular implementation, several other implementations have been developed.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Some of these are compilers or support JIT compilation, and hence offer performance benefits over Zend PHP at the expense of lacking full PHP compatibility.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP is free software released under the PHP License, which is equivalent to the 3-clause BSD license.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] This restriction on the use of "PHP" made the PHP License incompatible with the GNU General Public License (GPL), while the Zend License was incompatible due to an advertising clause similar to that of the original BSD license.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP includes various free and open-source libraries in its source distribution or uses them in resulting PHP binary builds.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP is fundamentally an Internet-aware system with built-in modules for accessing File Transfer Protocol (FTP) servers and many database servers, including PostgreSQL, MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server and SQLite (which is an embedded database), LDAP servers, and others.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Numerous functions are familiar to C programmers, such as those in the stdio family, are available in standard PHP builds.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP allows developers to write extensions in C to add functionality to the PHP language.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP extensions can be compiled statically into PHP or loaded dynamically at runtime.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Numerous extensions have been written to add support for the Windows API, process management on Unix-like operating systems, multibyte strings (Unicode), cURL, and several popular compression formats.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Other PHP features made available through extensions include integration with Internet Relay Chat (IRC), dynamic generation of images and Adobe Flash content, *PHP Data Objects* (PDO) as an abstraction layer used for accessing databases, and even speech synthesis.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Some of the language's core functions, such as those dealing with strings and arrays, are also implemented as extensions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The PHP Extension Community Library (PECL) project is a repository for extensions to the PHP language.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Most of the community focuses on web development, and PHP running server side (though also serving JavaScript for the client side), and some exceptional uses are for e.g. standalone graphical applications (with PHP-GTK unmaintained now for over a decade), and even drone control.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Some other projects, such as *Zephir*, provide the ability for PHP extensions to be created in a high-level language and compiled into native PHP extensions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Such an approach, instead of writing PHP extensions directly in C, simplifies the development of extensions and reduces the time required for programming and testing.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] By December 2018 the PHP Group consisted of ten people: Thies C.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Arntzen, Stig Bakken, Shane Caraveo, Andi Gutmans, Rasmus Lerdorf, Sam Ruby, Sascha Schumann, Zeev Suraski, Jim Winstead, and Andrei Zmievski.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Zend Technologies provides a PHP Certification based on PHP 8 exam (and previously based on PHP 7 and 5.5) for programmers to become certified PHP developers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] On 26 November 2021, the JetBrains blog announced the creation of The PHP Foundation, which will sponsor the design and development of PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The foundation hires "Core Developers" to work on the PHP language's core repository.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Roman Pronskiy, a member of the foundation's board, said that they aim to pay "market salaries" to developers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The response to the foundation has been largely positive.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund provided more than 200,000 Euros to support the PHP Foundation.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There are two primary ways for adding support for PHP to a web server – as a native web server module, or as a CGI executable.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP has a direct module interface called server application programming interface (SAPI), which is supported by many web servers including Apache HTTP Server, Microsoft IIS, Caddy (through FrankenPHP) and iPlanet Web Server.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Some other web servers, such as OmniHTTPd, support the Internet Server Application Programming Interface (ISAPI), which is Microsoft's web server module interface.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] If PHP has no module support for a web server, it can always be used as a Common Gateway Interface (CGI) or FastCGI processor; in that case, the web server is configured to use PHP's CGI executable to process all requests to PHP files.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP-FPM (FastCGI Process Manager) is an alternative FastCGI implementation for PHP, bundled with the official PHP distribution since version 5.3.3.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] When compared to the older FastCGI implementation, it contains some additional features, mostly useful for heavily loaded web servers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] When using PHP for command-line scripting, a PHP command-line interface (CLI) executable is needed.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP supports a CLI server application programming interface (SAPI) since PHP 4.3.0.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The main focus of this SAPI is developing shell applications using PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There are quite a few differences between the CLI SAPI and other SAPIs, although they do share many of the same behaviours.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] There are different kinds of SAPIs for various web server extensions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] For example, in addition to those listed above, other SAPIs for the PHP language include the Common Gateway Interface and command-line interface.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP can also be used for writing desktop graphical user interface (GUI) applications, by using the *"PHP Desktop".
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] *GitHub*.* or discontinued PHP-GTK extension.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] PHP-GTK is not included in the official PHP distribution, and as an extension, it can be used only with PHP versions 5.1.0 and newer.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The most common way of installing PHP-GTK is by compiling it from the source code.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] When PHP is installed and used in cloud environments, software development kits (SDKs) are provided for using cloud-specific features.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Numerous configuration options are supported, affecting both core PHP features and extensions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] Configuration file `php.ini` is searched for in different locations, depending on the way PHP is used.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p01] The configuration file is split into various sections, while some of the configuration options can be also set within the web server configuration.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP is a general-purpose scripting language that is especially suited to server-side web development, in which case PHP generally runs on a web server.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Any PHP code in a requested file is executed by the PHP runtime, usually to create dynamic web page content or dynamic images used on websites or elsewhere.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] It can also be used for command-line scripting and client-side graphical user interface (GUI) applications.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP can be deployed on most web servers, many operating systems and platforms, and can be used with many relational database management systems (RDBMS).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Most web hosting providers support PHP for use by their clients.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] It is available free of charge, and the PHP Group provides the complete source code for users to build, customize and extend for their own use.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP has also attracted the development of many software frameworks that provide building blocks and a design structure to promote rapid application development (RAD).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Some of these include PRADO, CakePHP, Symfony, CodeIgniter, Laravel, Yii Framework, Phalcon and Laminas, offering features similar to other web frameworks.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] The LAMP architecture has become popular in the web industry as a way of deploying web applications.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP is commonly used as the *P* in this bundle alongside Linux, Apache and MySQL, although the *P* may also refer to Python, Perl, or some mix of the three.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Similar packages, WAMP and MAMP, are also available for Windows and macOS, with the first letter standing for the respective operating system.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Although both PHP and Apache are provided as part of the macOS base install, users of these packages seek a simpler installation mechanism that can be more easily kept up to date.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] For specific and more advanced usage scenarios, PHP offers a well-defined and documented way for writing custom extensions in C or C++.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Besides extending the language itself in form of additional libraries, extensions are providing a way for improving execution speed where it is critical and there is room for improvements by using a true compiled language.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP also offers well-defined ways for embedding itself into other software projects.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] That way PHP can be easily used as an internal scripting language for another project, also providing tight interfacing with the project's specific internal data structures.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP received mixed reviews due to lacking support for multithreading at the core language level, though using threads is made possible by the "pthreads" PECL extension.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] A command line interface, php-cli, and two ActiveX Windows Script Host scripting engines for PHP have been produced.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP is used for Web content management systems including MediaWiki, WordPress, Joomla, Drupal, Moodle, eZ Publish, eZ Platform, and SilverStripe.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] As of January 2013, PHP was used in more than 240 million websites (39% of those sampled) and was installed on 2.1 million web servers.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] In 2019, 11% of all vulnerabilities listed by the National Vulnerability Database were linked to PHP; historically, about 30% of all vulnerabilities listed since 1996 in this database are linked to PHP.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Technical security flaws of the language itself or of its core libraries are not frequent (22 in 2009, about 1% of the total although PHP applies to about 20% of programs listed).
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Recognizing that programmers make mistakes, some languages include taint checking to automatically detect the lack of input validation which induces many issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Such a feature has been proposed for PHP in the past, but either been rejected or the proposal abandoned.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Third-party projects such as Suhosin and Snuffleupagus aim to remove or change dangerous parts of the language.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Historically, old versions of PHP had some configuration parameters and default values for such runtime settings that made some PHP applications prone to security issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Support for "magic quotes" and "register globals" settings has been deprecated since PHP 5.3.0, and removed from PHP 5.4.0.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] The best practice is to either locate the image directory outside the document root available to the web server and serve it via an intermediary script or disable PHP execution for the directory which stores the uploaded files.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Also, enabling the dynamic loading of PHP extensions (via `enable_dl` configuration directive) in a shared web hosting environment can lead to security issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Implied type conversions that result in different values being treated as equal, sometimes against the programmer's intent, can lead to security issues.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] For example, the result of the comparison `'0e1234' == '0'` is `true`, because strings that are parsable as numbers are converted to numbers; in this case, the first compared value is treated as scientific notation having the value (0×101234), which is zero.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] Errors like this resulted in authentication vulnerabilities in Simple Machines Forum, Typo3 and phpBB when MD5 password hashes were compared.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] The recommended way is to use `hash_equals()` (for timing attack safety), `strcmp` or the identity operator (`===`), as `'0e1234' === '0'` results in `false`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] In a 2013 analysis of over 170,000 website defacements, published by Zone-H, the most frequently (53%) used technique was the exploitation of file inclusion vulnerability, mostly related to insecure usage of the PHP language constructs `include`, `require`, and `allow_url_fopen`.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] PHP includes `rand()` and `mt_rand()` functions which use a pseudorandom number generator, and are not cryptographically secure.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] As of version 8.1, the `random_int()` function is included, which uses a cryptographically secure source of randomness provided by the system.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] There are two attacks that can be performed over PHP entropy sources: "seed attack" and "state recovery attack".
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] As of 2012, a $250 GPU can perform up to 230 MD5 calculations per second, while a $750 GPU can perform four times as many calculations at the same time.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] In combination with a "birthday attack" this can lead to serious security vulnerabilities.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] The PHP development team provides official bug fixes for two years following release of each minor version followed by another two years where only security fixes are released.
[src:ecommerce-magento/php-p02] After this, the release is considered end of life and no longer officially supported.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The software allows online shopping customers to accumulate a list of items for purchase.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] At the point of sale, the software typically calculates a total for the order, including freight transport, postage as well as packaging and labeling.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Associated taxes are calculated as applicable.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] This software also allows for a final review of the shortlisted purchase and the choice for a user to modify the purchase.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The data is used in online marketing particularly in the form of abandoned carts.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The development of web shop systems took place right after the Internet became a mass medium.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] This was a result of the launch of the browser Mosaic in 1993 and Netscape in 1994.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] It created an environment in which web shops were possible.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The Internet therefore acted as the key infrastructure development that contributed to the rapid diffusion of the e-commerce, a subset of e-business that describes all computer-aided business transactions.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] In 1998 a total of 11 e-business models were observed, one of which was e-shop business model for a B2C (business-to-consumer) business—also called the “online shop” The two terms “online shop” and “electronic” or “e-shop” are used interchangeably.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The term “online shopping” was invented much earlier in 1984.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Today the term primarily refers to the business-to-consumer transactional business.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] In order to enable “online shopping” a software system is needed.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Since “online shopping”, in the context of the B2C business model, became broadly available to the end consumer, internet-based “online shops” evolved.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] These applications typically provide a means of capturing a client's payment information, but in the case of a credit card they rely on the software module of the secure gateway provider, in conjunction with the secure payment gateway, in order to conduct secure credit card transactions online.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Some setup must be done in the HTML code of the website, and the shopping cart software must be installed on the server which hosts the site, or on the server which accepts sensitive ordering information.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] E-shopping carts are usually implemented using HTTP cookies or query strings.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] In most server based implementations however, data related to the shopping cart is kept in the session object and is accessed and manipulated on the fly, as the user selects different items from the cart.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Later in the process of finalizing the transaction, the information is accessed and an order is generated against the selected item thus clearing the shopping cart.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Although the most simple shopping carts strictly allow for an item to be added to a basket to start a checkout process (e.g., the free PayPal shopping cart), most shopping cart software provides additional features that an Internet merchant uses to fully manage an online store.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Data (products, categories, discounts, orders, customers, etc.) is normally stored in a database and accessed in real time by the software.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Shopping cart software is also known as e-commerce software, e-store software, online store software or storefront software and online shop.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The PCI security standards are a blanket of regulations set in place to safeguard payment account data security.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] The council that develops and monitors these regulations is composed of the leading providers in the payment industry: American Express, Discover Financial Services, JCB International, Mastercard, and Visa Inc.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Essentially, they define the best practices for storing, transmitting, and handling of sensitive information over the internet.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] Visa Inc. can hold shopping cart software providers responsible for liability that may occur as a result of non-compliance to Visa's regulations.
[src:ecommerce-magento/shopping-cart-software] For this reason, Visa Inc. may require that online merchants use shopping cart software providers from their list of PCI DSS-validated service providers.
